Saccharum spontaneum

   [1887.gif]
    Authority   L.
      Family    Liliopsida:Commelinidae:Cyperales:Gramineae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 1887

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A grass, free-tillering, often with aggressive
   rhizomes, reaching a height of up to 8 m, but normally it is 2-3.5 m.
   Culms slender, hard, pithy, often hollow, with little juice, and leaves
   100-200 cm long. USES It provides sugar, though the sucrose content is
   low and the fibre content high. Has been used in the breeding of S.
   officinarum, as it provides vigour, hardiness and resistance to many
   major diseases. GROWING PERIOD Perennial, growing 10-24 months, but
   most sugar cane is grown for 14-18 months for the plant crop and 12
   months for the ratoon crop. COMMON NAMES Wild cane, Pip-pit, Glagah,
   Tatebu, Talahib, Tigbau, Sidda, 'am'peu prei, Ph'ong, Lau, Phong, Lao,
   Co'lach. FURTHER INF Wild cane occurs in a wide region ranging from
   Africa and Afganistan to Japan and the South Pacific within the
   latitudinal range 40Â° to the equator. It can be found from sea level to
   1700 m in elevation. It natural habitats includes swamps, saline
   swamps, deserts, jungles, sandy river flats, and the low slopes of the
   Himalayas.

   Sources
   [10]Grassland Index
   Purseglove J 1972 pp 214-215 [USE]
   Skerman P 1990 pp 649-651 [DRA, RAIN, TEXT]
   Aronson J 1989 pp 69
   Mannetje L 1992 pp 195-196 [USE, RAIN, TEXT, FER]
   Lovett J 1979 pp 95-112 [DRA, SAL, TEXT]

